{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17524439","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17524439"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:04:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13994"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13994","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13994"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.71,0.19,0.02,0.02,0.06]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6628"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107418"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6628","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6628"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13994"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"325"},{"type":"tags","id":"449"},{"type":"tags","id":"469"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1553"},{"type":"tags","id":"1674"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4965"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5621"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"13453"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40016"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44304"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107418","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107418"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department following a motor vehicle accident, in which he was a front seat passenger. He was wearing his seat belt when the car was involved in a rear-end collision. His only complaint is of severe right-sided abdominal pain and swelling. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and is on warfarin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 94% on room air, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. There is a tender mass in the right lower quadrant of his abdomen. There is no rebound tenderness or guarding. His initial haemoglobin is 95 g/L (130-180). Repeat haemoglobin four hours later is 66 g/L, with the changes shown in the photograph (Image). His INR is 4.5 (0.8-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reversal of anticoagulation and blood transfusion","Immediate laparotomy","Ultrasound-guided drainage","Observation and serial haemoglobin measurements","Angiographic embolisation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a large right rectus sheath haematoma secondary to over-anticoagulation and trauma from a motor vehicle accident. The image shows a large haematoma within the right rectus sheath, which is the characteristic finding in this condition. The significant drop in haemoglobin indicates ongoing blood loss, and the elevated INR suggests over-anticoagulation (typical target for atrial fibrillation is an INR between 2-3).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate next step in management is \u003Cstrong\u003Ereversal of anticoagulation and blood transfusion\u003C/strong\u003E. This addresses both the underlying cause of the bleeding (over-anticoagulation) and the resultant anaemia. Reversal of anticoagulation typically involves administration of vitamin K and prothrombin complex concentrate. Blood transfusion is necessary due to the significant drop in haemoglobin and signs of haemodynamic instability (tachycardia and hypotension).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate laparotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated as the first step for a rectus sheath haematoma. These haematomas are typically self-limiting and can be managed conservatively. Surgery is reserved for cases where conservative management fails or if there are signs of abdominal compartment syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAngiographic embolisation\u003C/strong\u003E can be considered in cases of ongoing bleeding despite conservative management. However, it is not the first-line treatment and would only be considered if the patient remains unstable after reversal of anticoagulation and blood transfusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound-guided drainage\u003C/strong\u003E is generally not recommended for rectus sheath haematomas as it can potentially worsen bleeding and introduce infection. It may be considered in select cases of very large, liquefied haematomas causing significant discomfort.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObservation and serial haemoglobin measurements\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be insufficient in this case due to the patient\u0027s haemodynamic instability and significant drop in haemoglobin. This approach might be appropriate for smaller, stable haematomas in haemodynamically stable patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter initial stabilisation with anticoagulation reversal and blood transfusion, the patient should be closely monitored with serial haemoglobin measurements and repeat imaging if necessary. Most rectus sheath haematomas will resolve with conservative management, but surgical intervention may be required if bleeding persists or if there are signs of abdominal compartment syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Rectus sheath haematoma can be a life-threatening complication of anticoagulation, especially in elderly patients.","CT scan is the gold standard for diagnosing rectus sheath haematoma and assessing its extent.","Management of rectus sheath haematoma depends on the patient\u0027s haemodynamic stability and the size of the haematoma."],"references":["Hatjipetrou A, Anyfantakis D, Kastanakis M. Rectus sheath hematoma: A review of the literature. Int J Surg 2015; 13: 267-71. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/25529279/","Zomorrodi A, Picciola EA, Hotwagner DT. Determining the Need for Blood Transfusion. [Updated 2023 Jun 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564300/","Drinnon K, Simpson SS, Puckett Y, Ronaghan CA, Richmond RE. Rectus Sheath Hematoma: A Rare Surgical Emergency. Cureus. 2020 Dec 18;12(12):e12156. doi: 10.7759/cureus.12156. PMID: 33489568; PMCID: PMC7811892. Available from: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33489568/","Allen M, Sevensma KE. Rectus Sheath Hematoma. [Updated 2023 Jan 30]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2025 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK519033/","Yaddanapudi S, Yaddanapudi L. Indications for blood and blood product transfusion. Indian J Anaesth. 2014 Sep;58(5):538-42. doi: 10.4103/0019-5049.144648. PMID: 25535414; PMCID: PMC4260298. Available from: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4260298/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"89898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13994"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20885"},{"type":"media","id":"20886"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20885"},"attributes":{"m